   The Burgess deposits also yielded the oldest representative of the phylum Chordata, a small
   fossil known as Pikaia. Most specimens of Pikaia are between one and one and a half inches long.
   Chordates, the phylum to which humans belong, has three distinguishing characteristics, all of
   which are present in Pikaia. The extant animal known as a lancet bears at least a superficial
   resemblance to Pikaia.

