  The Cambrian Extinctions

   The Cambrian period is marked by as many as four mass extinctions. The first of these mass
   extinctions resulted in the disappearance of the archaeocyathids and a major group of
   trilobites. The later extinctions limited the diversity of conodonts, brachiopods, and other
   triolobite groups. The Cambrian is bracketed by large scale glaciation at the close of the
   Proterozoic and by a similar occurrence early in the Ordovician. Development of continental
   glaciers would have several consequences: cooling of the planet and a drop in sea level. Both of
   these might have happened quickly enough for a mass extinction to have resulted.

