   The Ordovician plant record consists solely of spored with a trilete mark, a y-shaped feature
   formed when the spores were formed by (presumably) meiosis. One possible interpretation of the
   presence of spores is that the land plant (trilete) spore have evolved prior to the move of
   plant ancestral types onto land.

   The vertebrates evolved during the Cambrian period, possibly from a creature similar to the
   Burgess Shale animal Pikaia or an organism similar to the "conodont" animal. The oldest group of
   fish, the ostracodemrs, first appeared during the Cambrian, before their extinction at the close
   of the devonian. The Ordovician. was a time of great transgression of the seas onto the
   continents, producing a great many habitats in which new forms of life, such as fish, could
   develop. The exact appearance of the Ordovician fish in unclear. What we do have is fragments of
   hard coverings of soft tissue.

