  The Silurian World

   Silurian climates were characterized by a warming and return to moderate temperatures following
   the terminal Ordovician glaciation (and the resulting mass extinction). North America remained
   near the equator, but began to join with Baltical to the east and Siberia to the north. Gondwana
   remained as a large southern hemisphere landmass, although there is no evidence of glaciation
   there during the Silurian. The collision of Baltica and North America caused mountain building
   (what geologists refer to as the Caledonian orogeny) along with the closing of the ancient
   Iapetus ocean. Between Baltica and Gondwana, however, a new ocean, Tethys, began to form. The
   end of the Silurian is not marked by a major mass extinction event.

